# This function checks if you don't have the correct packages installed yet
# If not, it will install it for you
packages <- c("tidyverse", "seasonal",
              "lubridate", "tidycensus", "forcats")
if (length(setdiff(packages, rownames(installed.packages()))) > 0) {
  install.packages(setdiff(packages, rownames(installed.packages())), repos = "https://cran.us.r-project.org")  
}

# load required packages
library(seasonal)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(tidycensus)
library(forcats)
# load background checks data
# scraped via tabula
checks <- read_csv("raw_data/scraped_background_checks_032021.csv")

# estimate gun sales based on background cheks
estimates <- checks %>%
  mutate(est_multiple = case_when(
            state=="California" ~ 0,
            TRUE ~ 2 * multiple),
         est_handgun = 1.1*handgun,
         est_long_gun = 1.1*long_gun,
         est_other = 1.1*other) %>% 
  select(month, state, est_multiple, 
         est_handgun, est_long_gun, est_other,
         private_sale_handgun,
         private_sale_long_gun, 
         private_sale_other) %>% 
  pivot_longer("est_multiple":"private_sale_other", names_to="type", values_to="count") %>% 
  group_by(month, state) %>% 
  summarize(estimate=sum(count, na.rm=T))

no_states <- c("Mariana Islands", "Virgin Islands", "Puerto Rico", 
               "Guam", "Hawaii")

# calculate national totals by month 
estimates_summary <- estimates %>%
  filter(!state %in% no_states) %>% 
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate, na.rm=T))  %>% 
  arrange(month)

# create time series 

last_month <- estimates %>% 
  arrange(desc(month)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  slice(1) %>% 
  pull(month)

latest_year <- gsub("-.*", "", last_month) %>% as.numeric()
latest_month <- gsub(".*-", "", last_month) %>% as.numeric()

estimates_summary_ts <- ts(estimates_summary$estimate, start=c(1998,11), end=c(latest_year, latest_month), frequency=12)
estimates_summary_ts <- window(estimates_summary_ts, start=c(2000,4), end=c(latest_year,latest_month))


# make seasonal adjustment, convert to data frame 
estimates_summary_seas <- seas(estimates_summary_ts)
estimates_seas <- as.data.frame(estimates_summary_seas) 

## Download population older than 18 from the census

#census_api_key("YOUR_CENSUS_API_KEY_HERE")

ages_list <- c("B01001_001", "B01001_003", "B01001_004", "B01001_005", "B01001_006",
  "B01001_027", "B01001_028", "B01001_029", "B01001_030")

for (i in 2009:2018) {
ages <- get_acs(geography = "state", variables = ages_list, year=i)
pop_df <- ages %>% 
  mutate(type=case_when(
    variable=="B01001_001" ~ "total",
    TRUE ~ "subtract"
  )) %>% 
  group_by(NAME, type) %>% 
  summarize(estimate=sum(estimate, na.rm=T)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from="type", values_from="estimate") %>% 
  mutate(adults=total-subtract) %>% 
  mutate(pc_over18=adults/total*100) %>% 
  rename(population=total, population_over18=adults) %>% 
  select(-subtract) %>% 
  mutate(year=i)
  print(i)
  if (i==2009) {
    pop <- pop_df
  } else {
    pop <- rbind(pop, pop_df)
  }
}

# no data for 2019 - 2021 so we're going to use the latest year of data
pop_df$year <- 2019
pop <- rbind(pop, pop_df)
pop_df$year <- 2020
pop <- rbind(pop, pop_df)
pop_df$year <- 2021
pop <- rbind(pop, pop_df)

pop <- pop %>% rename(state=NAME)
pop <- pop %>% 
  mutate(year=as.character(year))

# creat population summary data frame

pop_summary <- pop %>% 
  filter(state!="Puerto Rico") %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(population=sum(population),
           population_over18=sum(population_over18)) %>% 
  mutate(pc_over18=population_over18/population*100) %>% 
  mutate(year=as.character(year))

# join the data to seasonal gun estimates data
estimates_seas2 <- estimates_seas %>% 
  mutate(year=as.character(year(date))) %>% 
  inner_join(pop_summary, by="year") %>%
  mutate(rate = seasonaladj/population_over18*1000)
## visualize historical
ggplot(estimates_seas2, aes(x=date, y=rate)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title="National gun sales over time", y="Sales per 1,000 adults", x="")

## visualize year over year
estimates_seas2 <- estimates_seas2 %>% 
  mutate(month=month(date),
         year=year(date)) %>% 
  mutate(Year=case_when(
    year==2021 ~ "2021",
    year==2020 ~ "2020",
    year==2012 ~ "2012",
    year==2016 ~ "2016",
    TRUE ~ "Other years"
  ))
  
# functions to clean y axis labels
addUnits <- function(n) {
  labels <- ifelse(n < 1000, n,  # less than thousands
                   ifelse(n < 1e6, paste0(round(n/1e3), 'k'),  # in thousands
                          ifelse(n < 1e9, paste0(round(n/1e6, 1), 'M'),  # in millions
                                 ifelse(n < 1e12, paste0(round(n/1e9), 'B'), # in billions
                                        ifelse(n < 1e15, paste0(round(n/1e12), 'T'), # in trillions
                                               'too big!'
                                        )))))
  return(labels)
}


ggplot(estimates_seas2, aes(x=month, y=seasonaladj, color=Year, group=year)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = function(x) month.abb[x])+
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = addUnits) +
  labs(y="Firearm purchases", x="", title="Estimated national monthly firearm purchases",
       caption="Data: FBI NICS")
